Day 35: Deploying and Managing Applications on AWS

Step 1: Create a Private RDS MySQL Instance
Using AWS Console:
Login to AWS Console → go to RDS service.
Create Database:
Click Create Database.
Choose Standard Create or Sandbox Template (if available in your account).
Engine Options:
Engine type: MySQL
Version: 8.4.5
Templates:
Choose Free tier or Sandbox for testing.
DB Instance Settings:
DB instance identifier: datacenter-rds
Master username: datacenter_admin
Password: choose a secure password and confirm.
DB Instance Class:
Select: db.t3.micro
Storage:
Storage type: gp2
Allocated storage: 5 GiB
Connectivity:
VPC: choose your private VPC (so the DB is private)
Subnet group: leave default or ensure it is private
Public access: No
VPC security groups: we will adjust after creation to allow EC2 access
Database Options:
Database name: datacenter_db
Other Settings:
Keep defaults.
Create Database:
Click Create database.
Wait for the status to become Available.

Step 2: Adjust Security Groups
For the RDS Security Group:
Navigate to EC2 > Security Groups.
Select the RDS security group.
Add inbound rules to allow:
MySQL/Aurora (port 3306) from the private IP of datacenter-ec2 or its security group.
Optional: Allow port 80 if your EC2 instance also serves web traffic.

Step 3: Configure SSH Access to EC2
Connect to EC2 Console:
Go to EC2 Dashboard → Instances → select datacenter-ec2 → Connect.
Ensure SSH Key Exists:
On aws-client host:
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 2048 -f ~/.ssh/id_rsa
This will create /root/.ssh/id_rsa (private) and /root/.ssh/id_rsa.pub (public).
Add Public Key to EC2 Instance:
Connect to EC2 via browser or existing key.
Append the public key to /root/.ssh/authorized_keys:
echo "<contents-of-id_rsa.pub>" >> /root/.ssh/authorized_keys
chmod 600 /root/.ssh/authorized_keys

